1781105162979179	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyjBM		item.comment	bn-c5ui	{"body":"Starting fix: extracting run_post_merge_sanity + related types into a shared sync/sanity.rs module, then wiring up the check in resolve_structured.rs before auto-commit. Tests: (a) incident repro shape -- RS EOF appends → union → AST fail → warning + skip commit, (b) clean resolve still auto-commits, (c) non-rs (.txt) no warning."}	blake3:OOUmupeDYX5UcPSKMGDI9rXUX-0BWyaYbcbwd1z1QGk
1781105478995558	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyjRM		item.create	bn-1mn0	{"description":"Found in /tmp bang round 3 (debug build post-9d9b884c) re-verifying bn-39i8.\nRepro: standard 2-side content conflict (ws pb edits ln4 overlapping + ln9 clean),\nsidecar files deleted, `maw ws resolve pb --list` reconstructs (\"Reconstructed\nconflict metadata for 1 file(s)\") — good — but then `--keep epoch` silently used\nWHOLE-BLOB replace: pb's cleanly-merged ln9 edit was discarded (the exact bn-1nwn\nlossy behavior), the output line was bare \"resolved: fresh.txt\" (no per-hunk\nsuffix), and NO legacy-fallback warning printed.\nRoot cause (crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/resolve.rs, try_reconstruct_sidecar_from\n_placeholders): sides are built with `ConflictSide::new(ws_name, oid,\ndummy_ordering())` — `base_content` is never set, even though the `# base blob:`\nOID was parsed (it's stored only on `Conflict::Content.base`). The per-hunk --keep\npaths in resolve_structured.rs guard on side.base_content (keep-epoch:\nepoch_side.base_content; keep-<ws>: ws_side.base_content; keep-both uses\nContent.base) — so reconstructed sidecars silently fail the guard and degrade.\nFixes:\n1. In reconstruction, set base_content on the sides when a base OID was parsed\n   (check ConflictSide for the builder/field used by write path in materialize/\n   rebase so the semantics match bn-3mbj).\n2. Make the three per-hunk keep paths consistent: fall back to\n   `Conflict::Content.base` when `side.base_content` is None (covers older\n   sidecars AND reconstruction without requiring every producer to duplicate the\n   base into each side). Today keep-both already reads Content.base while\n   keep-epoch/keep-ws read side.base_content — unify via a small helper.\n3. When the per-hunk path is NOT taken for --keep epoch (no base anywhere), print\n   the same legacy-fallback warning the keep-<ws> path prints, so lossy whole-blob\n   replacement is never silent.\nTest: reconstruction test from bn-39i8 (conflict_state_truth.rs) extended to\nassert --keep epoch after reconstruction preserves the ws's cleanly-merged\ndisjoint edit (currently it would fail).\n","kind":"bug","title":"Reconstructed sidecars (bn-39i8) silently lose per-hunk --keep: sides lack base_content; keep paths guard on inconsistent base sources"}	blake3:w01dRnxNMX4KKsY16Jp3F8OWP6mC3IQ4cHHtmL9dk_E
1781105479277053	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyjhM		item.create	bn-heb8	{"description":"Found in /tmp bang round 3 (debug build post-9d9b884c). Epoch renames a file\n(git mv in a merged sibling), workspace edits the OLD path. Post-bn-566k this is\nno longer a silent resurrect (good) — it surfaces as [modify_delete] at the old\npath (deleter=epoch). But the stub gives no hint that the \"deletion\" was actually\na RENAME (the content lives on at renamed.txt in the epoch), and neither\nresolution can express \"carry my edit to the new path\":\n- --keep <ws>: old path resurrected WITH the edit, alongside epoch's renamed.txt\n  with the old content -> duplicated file, edit stranded at dead path\n- --keep epoch: old path stays deleted, the edit is DISCARDED silently (it's\n  still in git history, but nothing tells the user)\nImprovements (scope to taste): (1) when building the epoch delta, detect\ndelete+add pairs with identical/similar blob content (the merge engine already\nhas rename machinery — maw-core/src/merge/rename.rs) and annotate the\nmodify_delete stub + resolve --list output: \"note: epoch renamed this file to\n<new-path>; to carry your edit: maw exec <ws> -- git mv ... / apply edit at\n<new-path>\". (2) at minimum, --keep epoch on a modify_delete should print a\none-liner naming the discarded modifier blob OID so the edit is recoverable\nwithout git archaeology.\n","kind":"bug","title":"Epoch-rename vs ws-edit surfaces as bare modify_delete with no rename hint; --keep epoch silently discards the edit"}	blake3:-439WFuad1IwKB0OkvZphyPpIDEP2i6KE5wUeV7nVjs
1781105479548076	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyjxM		item.create	bn-ztu6	{"description":"Found in /tmp bang round 3 (debug build post-9d9b884c). Three workspaces: m1 and\nm2 edit the same line of fresh.txt (genuine overlap), m3 edits a different line\n(disjoint — `maw ws merge m1 m3 --check` and `m2 m3 --check` are both [OK]).\n`maw ws merge m1 m2 m3 --into default --check` reports:\n  C fresh.txt lines 2..3 [m1, m2, m3]: overlapping edits (diff3 conflict)\nm3 did not touch lines 2..3 and is not part of the conflict, but is listed as a\nparticipant. For an agent triaging which workspace must resolve, this misdirects\neffort (and in a real session would make an innocent workspace look blocked).\nExpected: the conflict record's side list should contain only the workspaces\nwhose edits overlap the conflicted region ([m1, m2]); m3's disjoint edit on the\nsame FILE should merge cleanly into the candidate. Likely in the merge engine's\nconflict record construction (maw-core/src/merge/ partition/plan/build) — the\nside list appears to be \"all sources touching the file\" rather than \"sources\nparty to the overlapping region\".\n","kind":"bug","title":"Multi-source merge --check misattributes conflicts: all sources listed as participants, not just the overlapping ones"}	blake3:p-ZucwKx7_dizP7adkoQ4WXdTbQrBDZOaCcK1pwUF30
