1781376799645392	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy4RM		item.create	bn-13g1	{"description":"Found 2026-06-13 while answering \"would the SG1 soak have caught the\norphan-commit bugs we just fixed (bn-29z8/1qtj/20sa/8flz)?\" Traced the\nharness end to end. Answer: NO — and not narrowly. The SG1 gate certifies\nfar less than \"the Prime Invariant holds in maw\"; it certifies \"the ref/\ncontent invariants hold in a hand-written MODEL of maw's git-object effects,\nunder fault injection.\" The orphan-commit class was out of scope BY\nCONSTRUCTION. This bears on what the v1.0 SG1 release-gate evidence (bn-2yzz)\nand the SG5 publication (bn-3ctu) may honestly claim.\n\nEVIDENCE (three independent reasons the orphan class is invisible):\n\n1. The action vocabulary cannot express the main vector.\n   The generator Op enum (crates/maw-scenario/src/lib.rs:259) is exactly:\n   WsCreate, EditFiles, Commit, Merge, Sync, Destroy, Recover. There is NO\n   Advance op. `maw ws advance` — the bn-8flz orphan vector (a 4th unguarded\n   HEAD-mover that orphaned committed work and printed \"advanced\n   successfully\") — literally cannot be generated at any seed/step count.\n\n2. The in-proc driver REIMPLEMENTS ops with raw git plumbing; it does not\n   run production maw-core / maw-git.\n   - in_proc.rs:598 do_merge synthesizes a merge with `git commit-tree` +\n     `update-ref` (commit message literally \"-> default (in-proc-driver)\"),\n     bumps refs/heads/main + refs/manifold/epoch/current to the last\n     source's tip, optionally destroys sources. It NEVER replays siblings\n     and NEVER calls set_head.\n   - in_proc.rs:657 do_sync is a literal NO-OP (\"Sync is a no-op at this\n     modelling level (no per-ws epoch staleness representation).\").\n   The orphan bug lived precisely in the code these stubs stand in for:\n   maw_git::set_head after the empty-replay walk (rebase.rs ~759), the\n   sibling auto-rebase triggered by merge, and the checkout fast-forward\n   path (bn-29z8/1qtj/20sa). None of that production code executes during\n   the soak. Because the model never moves a committed sibling's HEAD, it\n   cannot orphan one — so Oracle A/B run against an object graph the buggy\n   code never produced. Re-pinning the soak binary at the post-fix SHA does\n   NOT change this: the gap is the harness, not the pin.\n\n3. Sequential, single-process. The live incidents were multi-process races\n   (the bn-2yzz cron-setup agent merging while a worker's commit sat in a\n   sibling). drive()/drive_fast() apply plan steps one at a time in one\n   process (in_proc.rs:351). No inter-process HEAD race is modeled.\n\nWHAT THE GATE DOES COVER (be fair — it is not worthless):\n- Oracle A (oracle_a.rs): incremental blob/CONTENT reachability from the\n  frontier F = {epoch/current} U {refs/manifold/ws/*} U {extant ws HEADs}.\n  Catches irreversibly lost committed CONTENT. Note it deliberately checks\n  content, not commit identity.\n- Oracle B (oracle_b.rs): dangling head/owned refs + merge-state\n  incoherence — this is the bn-cm63 class the instrument was built to catch,\n  and it does.\nSo SG1 is a real model-checker of the ref/object invariants under the\nMODELED operations (merge/destroy/recover + fault injection). It just does\nnot exercise maw's actual workspace/HEAD-management code.\n\nIMPACT:\n- \"1e8 clean op-steps\" is meaningfully weaker than \"the Prime Invariant is\n  proven for maw.\" The strongest evidence for the orphan class is the FIELD\n  dogfooding that found it + the new always-loud guards (bn-20sa/8flz), not\n  the soak.\n- Risk: SG5 (bn-3ctu) publication / the v1.0 trust story must NOT claim the\n  soak covers HEAD-movement / concurrent-agent orphaning. Lead with the scar\n  (bn-cm63) AND scope the soak's claim honestly.\n\nREMEDIATION OPTIONS (decide scope for v1.0):\nA. Document the gate's scope precisely in notes/sg1-dst-architecture.md and\n   the SG5 publication: enumerate what the in-proc model does/does not\n   exercise (no Advance; do_merge/do_sync are models; single-process). Pair\n   with the field-dogfooding + guard evidence for the orphan class. (Cheap;\n   honest; does not widen coverage.)\nB. Widen the harness to actually run production code: add an Advance op;\n   make do_merge/do_sync invoke maw-core merge/sync (real set_head +\n   sibling auto-rebase) instead of the git-plumbing model; ideally model a\n   concurrent/interleaved set_head race. (Real T-work; would make the soak\n   cover the orphan class. May change throughput + determinism profile and\n   force a fresh campaign.)\nC. A targeted DST or property test JUST for the HEAD-movement choke-point\n   (set_head/checkout primitives) asserting reflog-trail + never-abandon,\n   complementary to the in-proc soak. (Middle cost.)\n\nRECOMMENDATION: at minimum A before v1.0 (the gate's published claim must\nmatch reality). Evaluate B/C as the higher-confidence path for the orphan\nclass. Keep the existing soak running meanwhile — it covers what it covers.\n\nDOES NOT BLOCK accrual mechanically, but SHOULD inform bn-2yzz's published\nrow and bn-3ctu (SG5) before the v1.0 tag.\n","kind":"bug","labels":["dst","assurance","v1-0"],"size":"l","title":"SG1 DST soak exercises a MODEL, not production HEAD-movement code — orphan-commit class is structurally invisible; gate over-states coverage"}	blake3:L6tN_tItOdUvfPERBQ3XkwAJDvKw0TU8hnHf6qjtT20
1781376812232018	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy4hM		item.link	bn-3ctu	{"link_type":"blocks","target":"bn-13g1"}	blake3:_xOPcMpt4eyrPr2rVW4q_9a5xnp0U0qUpir-KMGOJDU
1781376812300882	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy4xM		item.comment	bn-2yzz	{"body":"COVERAGE CAVEAT (bn-13g1, 2026-06-13): the in-proc soak exercises a git-plumbing MODEL, not production HEAD-movement code (no Advance op; do_merge/do_sync are models — do_sync is a no-op; single-process). So this 1e8 accrual certifies the ref/content invariants of the MODEL, NOT maw's actual set_head/auto-rebase/advance code — the orphan-commit class (bn-29z8/1qtj/20sa/8flz) is invisible to it. The published §7.1 row must scope the claim accordingly. See bn-13g1."}	blake3:OW0XhXMSnt-lpKnxFwXmJocRgdDxLyR7EvBKjShobpE
